WEBVTT

00:03.136 --> 00:08.083
Things he did was establish, for me, it was 
Wednesday morning meetings. Every other week, I

00:09.606 --> 00:12.871
had an audience with him. Now, either of us could 
call and cancel, and sometimes did, but not too

00:13.652 --> 00:18.459
often. And for an hour, I had his complete ear. We'd 
spend three or four minutes talking about what was

00:22.425 --> 00:27.032
on his mind, and then the rest of the time was mine. 
And the answer to the question is yes, very

00:27.613 --> 00:30.898
definitely yes. Back to your own style, a while ago 
I meant to ask and I think I interrupted myself. As

00:40.501 --> 00:58.084
department head, how much did you feel bound, I'd 
say it's in a faculty review, a promotion, a

00:40.501 --> 00:58.084
tenure, or an appointment, how much did you feel 
bound by the majority opinion of the department?

00:58.638 --> 01:00.401
compared to your own evaluation? For the most 
part, I felt the faculty's will ought to be served,

01:00.641 --> 01:09.796
but I wasn't afraid if there was... I only recall 
one time going against the faculty in a tenure

01:10.737 --> 01:20.713
decision, and of course I sent both 
recommendations forward, but Was yours negative

01:20.879 --> 01:23.161
compared to theirs? No, mine was positive and 
theirs was negative. Okay. In that particular

01:25.984 --> 01:29.288
instance, it could have gone the other way. What I 
made my faculty a promise with, one good example is

01:31.610 --> 01:38.157
new faculty hires. A promise I made them was that I 
would not hire someone that they didn't want, but I

01:39.098 --> 01:48.287
would not allow them to hire someone that I didn't 
want. And that worked pretty well in most things we

01:48.858 --> 01:51.842
dealt with. I don't, if I erred, I erred on the side 
of bringing the faculty in too much. I think they

01:58.770 --> 02:00.572
got weary of that toward the end. And I probably 
didn't use good judgment in some cases. During

02:05.218 --> 02:11.085
your years as department head, now in looking 
back, did the department miss any opportunities?

02:12.346 --> 02:16.131
We missed a big one right at the end of my tenure. I 
think, time will tell. We had an opportunity to

02:20.434 --> 02:23.638
develop a biomechanics lab. We had biomechanics 
as a specialty, but we didn't have a very good lab.

02:28.064 --> 02:30.607
We had an excellent exercise physiology lab. We 
had a very good motor learning lab. We had a chance

02:34.392 --> 02:38.297
to develop biomechanics, and I thought we should 
have done that. If we had done that, we'd be

02:39.018 --> 02:46.287
studying in a very scientific way the most 
efficient way of performing a sports skill, and

02:46.891 --> 02:54.142
might even could have landed one of the Olympic 
training centers on this campus. But the exercise

02:54.903 --> 02:58.689
physiology people at that time saw that as a 
threat. Because it was going to take some money to

02:59.249 --> 03:00.792
do that. That equipment is not cheap. And they saw 
that as money siphoning away from them. The motor

03:07.822 --> 03:09.625
learning felt the same way. And that was a case 
where the faculty carried the day. I didn't think

03:13.349 --> 03:18.334
that was a decision that needed to be unilaterally 
made. It was one that if enough people were against

03:18.355 --> 03:20.757
it, it would fail. I think we missed the boat there. 
I think we really should have done that. But time

03:27.464 --> 03:37.215
will tell, because what we have done instead is our 
exercise physiology program is twice as large now

03:27.464 --> 03:37.215
as it was. We have the only two distinguished 
professors in the College of Education are both in

03:37.550 --> 03:47.747
physical education, the current department head 
and Jack Wilmore, who was department head last

03:37.550 --> 03:47.747
year. That program I think very quickly will be, 
we're talking about top tens, I think very quickly

03:47.787 --> 04:01.870
they will be named among the top ten in the country 
and maybe in the top four or five. Now, in terms of

04:02.069 --> 04:05.436
Vision 2020, that's the right track to take. In 
terms of serving the people of Texas, I'm not so

04:07.380 --> 04:11.489
sure. Your health was what caused you to need to 
decide to step away from being department head, I

04:20.615 --> 04:22.539
presume. Well, no, actually not. I had decided 
that I was going to do that because I was reaching

04:24.002 --> 04:32.380
the point where I felt like Well, I lost my leader. 
Corrigan had stepped down as dean. And he had been

04:37.983 --> 04:41.589
my, let's see, one, two, three, my fourth dean. And 
as you know, you can only serve so many masters that

04:42.391 --> 04:46.357
way. Because every one of them changes a little, 
and that forces you to change your direction a

04:46.718 --> 04:51.326
little. And you tend to lose some of your 
consistency, I think. That had a lot to do with it.

04:59.459 --> 05:00.841
The other was I was growing tired. I'd been there a 
while, and I think they were a little tired of me

05:00.901 --> 05:05.487
too. And I enjoyed teaching, and I wanted to get 
back to that. I had already made the decision to

05:10.873 --> 05:19.984
retire, not retire, but to resign from the 
department of his job, and in fact had resigned

05:10.873 --> 05:19.984
before I was diagnosed with heart disease. And so 
what did you start doing, and what were your goals

05:20.004 --> 05:25.892
then as a full-time faculty member? I... I 
requested a study leave and was granted that. And

05:31.678 --> 05:34.092
so I went down to Baylor College of Medicine I have a 
good friend down that I had been working with all

05:34.358 --> 05:47.296
these years and took some courses there and also at 
the UT School of Public Health to try to recover my

05:34.358 --> 05:47.296
discipline a little because I obviously had lost 
my discipline by then. I came back and my goal was to

05:47.316 --> 06:02.037
spend the first year getting my classes laid out so 
that I felt comfortable then and then my second

05:47.316 --> 06:02.037
year I was going to focus on establishing a 
research agenda and I had full plans to to become a

06:02.472 --> 06:04.938
working active member of the faculty again.

06:07.825 --> 06:11.654
Because when I became a department head, I thought 
I was near the cutting edge of my field. I wanted to

06:11.895 --> 06:13.258
get back somewhere then. I made the first year all 
right, but it was in that first year that my wife was

06:13.897 --> 06:22.491
diagnosed with breast cancer and then I was 
diagnosed with heart disease. I'm afraid I didn't

06:24.695 --> 06:34.150
meet that latter goal because by then I was 
thinking pretty seriously about it was time to

06:24.695 --> 06:34.150
start thinking about retiring. But you're still 
full-time right now? I'm still full-time right

06:36.233 --> 06:37.294
now. And what are you working on? Well, this year, 
for the first year I haven't taught. I've been

06:42.700 --> 06:44.302
teaching a full load until this year. This year I 
bought my teaching time out with a chair. And what

06:48.167 --> 06:59.320
I'm attempting to do is get ready to turn loose the 
camp because that still is, I think, an important

06:48.167 --> 06:59.320
part of our department. I'm on the board of 
trustees for the Reed Youth Charities. And Mrs.

07:03.577 --> 07:11.365
Reed would like for me to continue to be the 
overseer of the camp even after retirement. And I

07:11.385 --> 07:12.567
may very well come back. In fact, the plan is to come 
back 25 percent of the time and do that. But this

07:16.951 --> 07:21.336
year what I've tried to do is locate some of our 
campers. We don't have real good follow-up work on

07:21.396 --> 07:25.220
where those youngsters are. Each one of them that 
go to that camp are guaranteed a scholarship to

07:25.240 --> 07:31.947
A&M. We haven't been moderately successful. 
They're all at-risk kids, and getting them in the

07:35.628 --> 07:39.174
university is real difficult. We've only had 
seven or eight or nine all the time we worked. But

07:42.640 --> 07:43.521
where are the rest of them? I'm convinced that 
we've done some good with those youngsters, but

07:43.702 --> 07:48.270
where are they now? So I've been trying to do some 
follow-up with them. And then also establish some

07:50.776 --> 08:00.408
relationship with school districts where they 
will help us identify youngsters who are at risk

07:50.776 --> 08:00.408
that we can give that same experience to. So I've 
been doing most of that this year. I had enough

08:03.352 --> 08:06.616
funds in the chair to do it once. I couldn't do that 
more than once. Of your almost 30 years here, To

08:13.557 --> 08:27.459
what administrators, deans, vice presidents, or 
provosts, presidents, chancellors, I'm not

08:13.557 --> 08:27.459
going to ask the negative, to which 
administrators would you give the highest marks

08:13.557 --> 08:27.459
for their leadership here at A&M? Well, I've 
always already said that Jack Williams was my

08:29.341 --> 08:34.830
hero, and I'll stick by that. I think he was 
outstanding. But he, in all honesty, he didn't

08:39.117 --> 08:41.961
have a lot of effect on me. other than 
peripherally,

08:42.177 --> 08:46.956
the president that, I knew Jarvis Miller very 
well. His daughter and my daughter played in the

08:49.862 --> 09:05.784
orchestra, the Rises Valley Orchestra, and I was 
with him on a trip to see our girls play the week

08:49.862 --> 09:05.784
before he was named president the next week, and I 
didn't have a clue that was going to happen. So I

09:07.766 --> 09:14.175
knew him well, but I have to say Frank Vandiver 
probably was the next president that I was most

09:15.252 --> 09:16.774
impacted by. He had a tumultuous administration, 
but gosh, he was good to work with.

09:30.755 --> 09:35.441
You recall the days when seniors didn't have to 
take final tests. The faculty senate decided to

09:36.102 --> 09:39.347
dig their heels in, and we were going to change 
this. And we went to his office. to hear the words

09:44.328 --> 09:48.182
spoken by him that it ain't gonna fly. And we were 
able to sit there and work out and negotiate a

09:49.446 --> 09:56.852
compromise. that when we hit upon it, it was almost 
like he knew this is what should happen, but he was

09:57.136 --> 10:07.446
waiting for us to say it and walked away from there 
feeling real good about it. And in fact, we got it

10:07.466 --> 10:09.127
done. He was a faculty member's department 
president, I think. I think he never was

10:12.991 --> 10:16.254
comfortable being a president. He was still a 
faculty member. So from that point of view, those

10:18.336 --> 10:21.539
were the two that I thought the most of. I really 
only worked... a reasonable time with two deans,

10:26.026 --> 10:33.737
Hubert when I was a faculty member and then later on 
as department head. Lembacher, Phil Lembacher

10:34.699 --> 10:44.132
was acting for a year and he was very, very helpful 
because I was a brand new department head, didn't

10:34.699 --> 10:44.132
know, come here from Sycam and he helped me an awful 
lot. But then Corrigan would have to be my pick

10:44.713 --> 10:50.041
there. I worked with Chris Borman as an acting dean 
for a while. And then I only served one year under

10:54.764 --> 10:57.708
Jane Stallings.

10:59.890 --> 11:07.299
So at the dean's level, I thought that was, Cargan 
would be my pick. I only worked for one department

11:08.301 --> 11:22.358
head here, and that was, well, no, actually, Carl 
Landis was the department head, but I worked with

11:08.301 --> 11:22.358
Bob Armstrong, who's the current department 
head, and Jack Wilmore, but it was after I had been

11:08.301 --> 11:22.358
in that role, and they pretty well left me alone, 
and I didn't, I didn't and I tried to stay out of

11:22.810 --> 11:24.432
their way. So I have to say in retrospect that Carl 
was really fun to work for and that's surprising me

11:26.315 --> 11:37.311
that I can say that today because my first three or 
four years I wouldn't have told you that at all. Are

11:38.112 --> 11:46.945
there other people related to your A&M experience 
if they could be brought into this room that you

11:38.112 --> 11:46.945
would want to express appreciation to? Oh, gosh, 
yes. Brian Cole was really helpful. Particularly

11:54.411 --> 11:56.594
after I became department head, he was helpful. 
Because he was then the assistant. He was then

11:59.017 --> 12:06.206
assistant to the dean and became, before I left the 
office, he became associate dean and took

11:59.017 --> 12:06.206
Limbacher's position. He was really good to work 
with. And Cargan was wise enough to turn a lot of

12:11.052 --> 12:15.818
things over to him. That's in the college level. 
I'll always appreciate Chris Borman, because he

12:18.452 --> 12:23.459
took a thankless job and did it. I don't think we 
were, as a university, was quite straight with

12:25.282 --> 12:36.519
him, because he took the acting dean's job 
thinking he had a chance to be dean, and really

12:25.282 --> 12:36.519
didn't have a chance. In the upper 
administration, Chuck McCandless was

12:37.561 --> 12:40.746
outstanding. Of course, he understood us. I loved 
that guy like a brother almost, and he was neat.

12:51.578 --> 12:54.701
I've forgotten who was provost that went to Iowa 
State. It may have been your friend that called you

12:54.761 --> 12:57.444
about the basketball club. Oh, no, no. Former dean 
of geosciences. Right, that's right. I really

13:04.911 --> 13:08.514
liked him an awful lot. You were gone by the time he 
came aboard, weren't you? He did a very nice job.

13:15.029 --> 13:22.257
Let's see, some goofy moments in your A&M 
experience? I took the liberty of trying to think

13:22.277 --> 13:24.519
of a few of those. One was, remember Howard Vestal? 
Sure. Howard Vestal erected a stop sign in the

13:28.103 --> 13:36.331
middle of a block right across from Rudder Tower. 
This was after you, I think you may have been in

13:38.674 --> 13:42.758
Missouri at that time, but he came out of his office 
one day and almost got hit by a car, came back the

13:43.244 --> 13:49.172
next day and ruled that they were going to put a stop 
sign up. And he had a stop sign right in the middle of

13:49.192 --> 13:52.376
that intersection where he crossed. And cars 
would . And 30 minutes after he retired, that stop

13:55.620 --> 14:00.867
sign came down. That's a good one. I thought that 
was outstanding.

14:08.641 --> 14:12.966
Pranks that anybody ever played on the department 
head while you were the department head? I don't

14:14.868 --> 14:19.494
know whether it was a prank or not, but God played a 
prank on us. My first year as department head, the

14:19.714 --> 14:23.759
snow melted on Mount Aggie.

14:26.682 --> 14:27.903
I think you were still here then. Well, I know what 
Mount Aggie was. Yeah, okay. We had AstroTurf on

14:32.114 --> 14:46.935
Mount Aggie, and Carl Landis retired, but one of 
the last things he did was buy something called SNO

14:32.114 --> 14:46.935
something. I forgot what it was. Snow Flow or 
something like that. It was a black surface. It had

14:51.341 --> 14:55.047
prongs sticking up on it, and the kids really liked 
it. The teachers liked it because it really would

14:55.107 --> 14:58.712
give you the feel of edging in snow. The only 
problem is when the weather got the slightest bit

14:59.283 --> 15:08.074
cool that fall, that brittle, and they'd pop off 
just like machines. And so I got a phone call. Chip,

15:13.020 --> 15:19.889
what's Chip's name, works down at the TV station, 
one of the radio stations in town, Chip Howard.

15:20.430 --> 15:22.492
Chip Howard wanted to interview me. And, of 
course, I'd only been on the job just a few weeks,

15:22.512 --> 15:25.476
and I thought, Oh, Lord, I am going to embarrass the 
whole university. And what he wanted to envy me

15:28.653 --> 15:34.002
about was the snow that melted on Mount Aggie. And I 
went to great detail to explain to him that we were

15:34.022 --> 15:40.572
careful not to waste the university's money. I 
surely thought he was on a witch hunt when he came.

15:45.058 --> 15:50.046
Probably the worst thing that happened to me It 
happened in 1986. We had a teacher, she's still on

15:51.805 --> 15:58.652
our faculty, a very fine teacher. And she taught 
outdoor, what we called outdoor education. And in

16:02.481 --> 16:08.072
that program was a weekend camping trip where they 
would go out to the wilderness someplace. And in

16:08.132 --> 16:14.524
this case, they went to Enchanted Rock out near 
Kerrville and would rock climb at the backside of

16:08.132 --> 16:14.524
that rock. And she did some really neat things with 
those youngsters. That was the safest thing they

16:19.113 --> 16:22.159
did was rock climbing, in fact. But she did some 
really neat things with those kids and we have a

16:22.139 --> 16:33.261
ropes course that she developed and a lot of 
business executives go through that building

16:22.139 --> 16:33.261
team and that kind of thing. But she had gone by 
automobile and she had six people in a car and on the

16:34.443 --> 16:41.076
way back, Out there where the east loop joins 21, 
she was ahead of this particular, I don't know if

16:41.663 --> 17:05.477
there's a car ahead of them or not, but she was ahead 
of one car and she exited on to the sixth loop and she

16:41.663 --> 17:05.477
said she looked in the rearview mirror and saw the 
other car missed the turn and remarked did they

16:41.663 --> 17:05.477
miss the turn. What they did was they went down 
another few blocks and realized they'd missed the

17:05.879 --> 17:21.440
turn, pulled over, and then made a U-turn right in 
front of a tractor truck, and it killed five of

17:05.879 --> 17:21.440
those kids, and one of them was Robert Walker's 
son, Richard. I'm telling you, I'm still fragile

17:23.542 --> 17:27.828
about that. It's the worst thing that can happen to 
anyone. To a lesser degree, I understood what

17:35.697 --> 17:39.521
President Bowen was going through with the 
bonfire thing. It just eats your guts right out.

17:43.405 --> 17:46.268
And I don't think I ever recovered from that 
totally. It's something I remember, but I don't

17:46.368 --> 17:50.432
want to remember it. Yes. And Bob Walker and his 
wife Joanne were rocks. I mean, just strong,

17:58.601 --> 18:01.985
strong faith. That's right. Absolutely.

